Research Inspirations
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------

The following research papers and projects influenced design decisions in this
software. No code was copied; these are algorithmic and methodological
inspirations with original implementations.

  Prompt Engineering:
    EmotionPrompt (Li et al., CAS + Microsoft, 2023)
      Emotional stimulus appended to prompts improves instruction-following.
      Used in: src/agents/refine.ts

    OPRO (Yang et al., Google DeepMind, 2023)
      Optimization by PROmpting — outperforms chain-of-thought on benchmarks.
      Used in: src/agents/refine.ts

    Self-Consistency (Wang et al., 2022)
      Multi-path reasoning with majority vote reduces careless errors.
      Used in: src/agents/refine.ts

  Evaluation:
    MT-Bench (Zheng et al., 2023)
      LLM-as-judge methodology; GPT-4 judge achieves >80% human agreement.
      Used in: src/agents/judge.ts

    Promptfoo llm-rubric
      Output schema pattern: {reason, score, pass}.
      Used in: src/agents/judge.ts

  Architecture:
    GitNexus knowledge-graph approach
      Inspired the project-index connectivity-based clustering design.
      Used in: src/project-index.ts (implemented from scratch, no shared code)

  Algorithms (standard, published knowledge):
    BM25 (Robertson et al., 1994) — term frequency scoring
    Union-Find / Disjoint Set Union — graph clustering
    Wilson Score Lower Bound — binomial confidence intervals
    Mulberry32 — seeded pseudo-random number generator

  External Data:
    awesome-claude-code-toolkit (rohitg00/awesome-claude-code-toolkit, MIT)
      MCP preset configs, CLAUDE.md templates, and hook seeds fetched at runtime.
      Used in: src/mcp-presets.ts, src/commands/init-command.ts,
               src/cli/seed-toolkit-command.ts, src/cli/hooks-command.ts

